&lt;b&gt;Bible:&lt;/b&gt; Genesis 7:17&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Length:&lt;/b&gt; 37 min. (64kbps)

&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&lt;b&gt;Overview:&lt;/b&gt; Can a doctrine be found in the account of the Noahic Flood where we read of the rising floodwaters and the bearing up and lifting up of the Ark above the earth?  Or do the words of our text merely further the narrative of this biblical passage?  Were the floodwaters an instrument in God's hand for death or life, for judgement or salvation?  Were others saved in the Ark beyond Noah, his family, and the all the animals?  What does the coming of the Messiah have to do with the Noachian Flood?  Does this Great Deluge contain a divine paradox?  Can we find the Gospel within such a paradox?  Does God offer hope in the midst of this universal destruction?  Come and listen and see.</description>
</item>
